TY  - JOUR
ID  - EJ1480298
TI  - Sorting through Garbage: An Autoethnography of Decision-Making Impacts on Instructional Designers in Organizational Anarchies
AU  - Rebecca Clark-Stallkamp
AB  - This narrative autoethnography explores how non-normative decision-making processes within higher education institutions impact instructional designers' work. Drawing on 13 months of reflective journaling, the author examines their experience navigating a university operating as an organized anarchy through the lens of Cohen et al.'s (1972) Garbage Can Model. The study highlights how decisions made by oversight or flight--often without input from instructional designers--create ethical tensions, misaligned priorities, and disruptions to instructional design processes. Through critical reflection, three themes emerged: managing uncertainty, navigating oversight and flight decisions, and practicing reflexive advocacy. These findings reframe instructional designers' adaptability as a strategic, epistemic response to institutional ambiguity. The paper extends Schön's concept of the reflective practitioner by introducing &quot;reflexive advocacy&quot;--proactive strategies for negotiating constraints while maintaining design integrity. This work offers practical insights for instructional designers and contributes to a growing body of literature examining the organizational contexts in which instructional design occurs.
PY  - 2025
